 But then the auto-grader has its own set of rules.

17
00:00:55,800 --> 00:00:58,960
 And so it puts these codes in various places.

18
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:04,500
 That's one of the ways the auto-grader tracks whether or not stuff is moved between students.

19
00:01:04,500 --> 00:01:10,840
 And so that you're grading your version of this, not someone else's application, okay?

20
00:01:10,840 --> 00:01:16,200
 So let me show you a little bit about what happens right when you're going to press this

21
00:01:16,200 --> 00:01:18,100
 evaluate button.

22
00:01:18,100 --> 00:01:21,520
 So this is a couple of slides I have on how the auto-grader works.

23
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:22,560
 So what is it?

24
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:27,520
 So the auto-grader is a piece of software that I wrote on www.dj4e.com, it's launched

25
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:29,560
 from Canvas or Coursera.

26
00:01:29,560 --> 00:01:33,360
 That is going to grade your assignment, check to make sure it's okay.

27
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,600
 And it's a very simple program.

28
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:40,040
 If you took Python for everybody, you wrote a program that does web crawling.

29
00:01:40,040 --> 00:01:45,640
 So what this is is just a smart web crawler that decides if your page meets a certain

30
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:47,720
 set of specifications and then gives it a grade.

31
00:01:47,720 --> 00:01:52,600
 So it sends requests the webpage and it checks the response to make sure that it's right,

32
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:54,600
 then continues to the next page.

33
00:01:54,600 --> 00:01:59,560
 And if it makes it all the way through all of the tests, then a correct grade is sent

34
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:00,840
 back to Canvas.

35
00:02:00,840 --> 00:02:02,760
 So I have an philosophy and approach.

36
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:04,560
 I'm trying to make these simple.

37
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:06,680
 Sometimes there's auto-graders that try to trick you.

38
00:02:06,680 --> 00:02:08,720
 I want to keep it as simple as possible.

39
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:11,360
 I want to just check to see did you follow the instructions, right?

40
00:02:11,360 --> 00:02:15,000
 And you'll make lots of little mistakes and this auto-grader is going to catch them.

41
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:16,480
 I give you a lot of feedback.

42
00:02:16,480 --> 00:02:19,400
 I try not to make the auto-grader mysterious.

43
00:02:19,400 --> 00:02:23,120
 Although you will think I'm doing that, it is not true.

44
00:02:23,120 --> 00:02:25,440
 All it does is did you check the instructions?

45
00:02:25,440 --> 00:02:29,680
 It's doing the simplest thing it can possibly can, which is not always super simple.

46
00:02:29,680 --> 00:02:32,960
 So there's no guarantee that the AI-generated code that looks good in the browser is going

47
00:02:32,960 --> 00:02:34,700
 to pass the auto-grader.

48
00:02:34,700 --> 00:02:39,920
 And so you can't come and say, "Look, it has a button and it says the word hello world."

49
00:02:39,920 --> 00:02:43,720
 Well, it might be that it's the wrong kind of button or you're using an anchor tag or

50
00:02:43,720 --> 00:02:45,880
 a button tag because AI just did it.

51
00:02:45,880 --> 00:02:48,800
 Because AI can build code an infinite number of ways.

52
00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:52,080
 If you follow my instructions, you tend to build it one way.

53
00:02:52,080 --> 00:02:54,880
 And that's what the auto-grader is looking for.

54
00:02:54,880 --> 00:02:57,800
 Did you follow the instructions?

55
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:00,960
 Follow the instructions, doing your own work, and then the auto-grader is going to take

56
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:04,800
 you to the bugs, give you a grade when you fix those bugs, and it should be straightforward.

57
00:03:04,800 --> 00:03:08,640
 I'm not saying you can't use AI on the way.

58
00:03:08,640 --> 00:03:12,580
 So here's kind of a block diagram of how this process works.

59
00:03:12,580 --> 00:03:17,400
 So you're developing, say, your website on drchuckpythonanywhere.com, you're using a

60
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:21,580
 browser and you're clicking on it and you're hitting refresh and you're getting errors

61
00:03:21,580 --> 00:03:24,400
 and you're fixing the errors and reloading your application.

62
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:30,040
 So that top process of just developing and testing is really important.

63
00:03:30,040 --> 00:03:34,120
 And some of the auto-graders or assignments will give you manual testing.

64
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:38,240
 And I think it's really important for you to manually test first.

65
00:03:38,240 --> 00:03:41,640
 And then hopefully when it all works and you've manually tested it, then it's time to send

66
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:43,400
 it to the auto-grader.

67
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:50,680
 And so you go in from your learning management system, launches into djangoforeverybody.com

68
00:03:50,680 --> 00:03:55,120
 with an LTI token, and then you press the evaluate button.

69
00:03:55,120 --> 00:04:01,780
 And then what happens is djfree.com makes its own connections to your website and it

70
00:04:01,780 --> 00:04:06,120
 sends requests and it receives HTML back and it reads that HTML.

71
00:04:06,120 --> 00:04:10,160
 And based on what that HTML is, it either says, "Whoops, I got the wrong thing," or

72
00:04:10,160 --> 00:04:16,640
 it goes on and then eventually using Learning Tools Interoperability, it sends a grade back

73
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:19,600
 to Canvas or Coursera.

74
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:23,640
 In the first auto-grader that we're going to show here, it really just does one, but

75
00:04:23,640 --> 00:04:30,340
 you can get toward the end and djfree.com will make up to 50 request response cycles.

76
00:04:30,340 --> 00:04:34,560
 And it's got a lot of debug output and so you're going to have to scroll down.

